          <h3>Basslines from the Broken Earth: Wormhole Transmissions from the Rim of the World</h3>
					<p>At 3:03 AM on the summer solstice, our salvaged antenna lit up with a strange new frequency—not our music, but a pulsing thrum filled with future weather reports, fungal poetry, and glitching voices repeating.</p> 
					<blockquote class="block-quote">
						"Highway 18. Mile marker * garbled signal *. Rim of the World."
					</blockquote>
					<p>Our SDR display flickered, went black, relit, and then locked onto a voice that sounded like rust and rain.</p>
					<blockquote class="block-quote">
						“The root-net is live. Tune in. The Earth is speaking. You are a caregiver of my signal now.”
					</blockquote>
					<p>Within the hour, We were packed in the van and racing to re-broadcast transmissions from the wormhole at the Rim of the World.</p>
					<p class="text-red"><strong>Here's what we know so far after a lot of digging, soil sampling, and guessing.</strong></p>
					<p>Beneath the cracked asphalt of Highway 18, a pine grove began a silent transformation. Parched and stressed by the relentless heat, the trees turned to the road’s toxic remnants—metals from brake dust, batteries, and discarded electronics for sustenance. Their roots absorbed the elements and fused them with fungal threads into a glittering system of earthen circuits. Over time, a hidden, living network formed—part plant and part machine.</p>
					<p>Then, on a storm-charged summer solstice night, the roots ignited with neural fire. The ground split. Time shattered. And at the forest’s edge, a wormhole opened—pulsing with Earth’s subharmoics and futures no longer willing to wait. Our crew at KDZU caught the wormhole’s transmissions first as the broadcast was stepping on the signal of our transmitter. We thought it might be Federal Agents and eventaully figured out it was a transmission from Earth and from future timelines.</p>
